Defendant Willie J Holland in court with attorney Richard A. Sachs.  Defendant Willie J Holland in custody.  
Megan Patricia Carmody appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  
Deputy Court Clerk: dds.

Defendant prepared to enter change of plea.  Hearing proceeded.  Negotiations set forth by the state including uncharged read-in (battery to prisoner).

COUNT 1:  The defendant was advised of his constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, plead GUILTY and was examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights, Addendum to Plea Questionnaire, and Jury Instructions received and filed.  The parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis for the plea.  The Court found the defendant guilty and ordered entry of Judgment of Conviction.  Pursuant to Wisconsin Statutes Section 973.176, the Court advised the defendant of the following restrictions:  Firearm possession and Voting.  

COUNT 2:  Pursuant to plea negotiations and on state's motion, the Court orders this case DISMISSED AND READ-IN.


Sentencing proceeded.  Statements made by State, defense, Yaldiz D., and defendant. 
 
The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 7 YEARS, CONSECUTIVE to any other time being served with credit for 451 days served. The INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 3 YEARS.  The MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION IS 4 YEARS.

The defendant IS eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program AFTER SERVING THE FIRST 2 YEARS OF THIS SENTENCE.  The defendant IS NOT eligible for the Substance Abuse Program.

CONDITIONS OF SUPERVISION EXTENDED:
*Obtain Mental health assessment- successfully complete follow-up treatment-take any prescription medication only in the manner as prescribed by physician;
*Obtain AODA assessment and if necessary successfully complete follow-up treatment;
*Cooperate with random urine screens;
*No drug dealing or association with drug community (drug users/dealers or drug houses);
*Cooperate with any and all rules set forth by the probation agent;
*No new law violations rising to the level of probable cause;
*No contact with victim Conlin B. and Aaron H.;
*Obtain/maintain employment and work hours to the extent allowed (not to affect ssi benefits;
*Participate (optional) in Vocational training- department to assist if defendant interested;
*Participate in Anger management- can be as part of mental health programming or separately;
*Obtain GED or HSED;
*Pay all supervision fees;
*Provide DNA sample if not previously done so- pay surcharge;
*Pay all applicable mandatory surcharges, fees, assessments, and costs; 

State in compliance with victim rights legislation.  The Court ordered restitution set at zero.  The Court ordered that all financial obligations be paid through collection of sums by the Department of Corrections from 25% of funds under Sec. 973.05(4)(b) and as a condition of extended supervision.  Any amount remaining due and owing is subject to civil judgment.  Pursuant to Wisconsin Statutes Section 973.176, the Court advised the defendant of the following restrictions:  Firearm possession and Voting.  Appeal rights given.
